Movie: Home Alone 2: Lost in New York
Portrait of a Lady on Fire
Back to the Future Part II

Review: a closer feeling of what linklater captures in the first film, but now you get a more complex and raw relationship. you don´t a whole picture of how their life has been since the last film, but you get glimpses through pieces and pieces that get revealed in their fight. seeing them fight the whole third act feels devastating. their reunion with their romantic side on the last film becomes a slideshow of bitter and resentful moments throught their relationship…
confusing nonsense. the incredible imagery and the dizzying plot creates a hypnotic experience. kind of noir, kind of a fashion film. style won the battle once again.
I'll always get onboard with this level of unhinged, but many parts of it felt very pointless.

it's been a long time since i felt so much empathy with a character. for 90 minutes we watch this poor bastard crawl through life, walking towards his foretold death. van sant really does it like no one else could. we feel the dread, the loudness, the weariness. i loved the use of sound, creating that dazed echoing sensation inside the protagonist's head. the monotony and repetition of moments make this world feel like an inescapable nightmare.
wasn´t expecting a reinterpretation of 9/11 through an American godzilla figure
nothing shows you the anxiety and fears of parenthood better than a deranged french woman breaking into your home
